Here's a function in Julia that accomplishes the task:
```julia
function add_yearmonth(df::DataFrame)
    @transform(df, ym = string(year(dt), zero_padding(month(dt), 2)))
end

function zero_padding(val, padding)
    return lpad(val, padding, '0')
end
```
This function takes a DataFrame as input and returns the same DataFrame with an additional column `ym`. The new column is created by extracting year and month from the `dt` column using the built-in `year()` and `month()` functions respectively. Then, these values are concatenated together as strings in the format "yyyymm" using string interpolation. The function also includes an additional helper function called `zero_padding()` to ensure that months are always represented with two digits (e.g., 01 for January).
